# WardrobeAI — Cursor Rules

## Project Overview
WardrobeAI is a Next.js 14 app where users scan their wardrobe, organize clothing, build outfits,
plan weekly looks, and receive AI-powered shopping suggestions based on body proportions, style
preferences, weather, and location.

## Tech Stack
- Framework: Next.js 14 (App Router)
- Database & Auth: Supabase
- Storage: Supabase Storage
- Styling: Tailwind CSS
- AI: Google Gemini 2.0 Flash (`@google/generative-ai`)
- Weather: OpenWeatherMap API
- Hosting: Vercel

---

## Code Style & Patterns

### General
- Use TypeScript for every file. No `any` types — define proper interfaces in `types/index.ts`.
- Named exports for components. Default exports only for page files.
- All async operations must have try/catch with proper error handling.
- Never use `console.log` in production paths — use the logger utility in `lib/utils/logger.ts`.
- Keep components under ~150 lines. If a component exceeds this, break it into sub-components.

### Next.js
- App Router exclusively. No Pages Router patterns ever.
- Server Components by default. Add `"use client"` only when needed (hooks, interactivity, browser APIs).
- All API routes live in `app/api/`. Validate request body before any processing.
- Use Next.js `<Image>` for all images. Never use raw `<img>` tags.
- Server-side secrets stay in server components and API routes ONLY. Never expose to the client.

### Supabase
- All database queries go through server-side API routes or Server Components. Never query Supabase from client components.
- Every table must have Row Level Security (RLS) enabled and policies defined.
- Use Supabase Storage for all image uploads (wardrobe photos, user body photos).
- Always verify the authenticated user owns a resource before any read/write/delete operation.
- Use Supabase Auth for all authentication. No custom auth solutions.

### Tailwind CSS
- Tailwind utility classes only. No inline styles. No external CSS files unless absolutely necessary.
- Use the design tokens defined in `tailwind.config.ts` for colors, spacing, and fonts.
- Mobile-first responsive design. Every layout must be usable on mobile.
- Extract repeated long className strings into components rather than duplicating them.

### Gemini
- All Gemini API calls are server-side only. Never call the Gemini API from a client component.
- Images must be fetched server-side from Supabase Storage and converted to base64 before passing to Gemini. Never pass raw URLs to the Gemini API.
- Always validate and sanitize AI responses before storing or displaying them.
- Include fallback UI for when AI calls fail or return unexpected output.
- Cache AI results in the database. If a wardrobe item already has `ai_analyzed = true`, skip the API call.
- Rate limit all AI-powered routes using the limits defined in `instructions/ai-integration.md`.

### Components
- All reusable UI primitives live in `components/ui/`.
- Feature components live in their feature folder (`components/wardrobe/`, `components/outfits/`, etc.).
- Always use existing Button, Card, Modal, LoadingSpinner, and Badge components. Do not create duplicates.
- Every interactive element must have a loading state and an error state.

### Forms & Validation
- Use React Hook Form for all forms.
- Validate on both client and server. Never trust client input alone.

