## Naming Conventions
- Components: PascalCase (`WardrobeItemCard.tsx`)
- Hooks: camelCase with `use` prefix (`useWardrobe.ts`)
- Utilities: camelCase (`formatDate.ts`)
- Types/Interfaces: PascalCase (`WardrobeItem`, `OutfitPlan`)
- API route folders: kebab-case (`app/api/wardrobe-items/route.ts`)
- Database tables: snake_case (`wardrobe_items`, `outfit_plans`)

---

## Security Rules
- Never put API keys, secrets, or tokens in client-side code.
- Confirm `.env.local` is in `.gitignore` before first commit.
- Always check ownership before returning or modifying any user data.
- Sanitize all user input before storing it.
- Show generic error messages to users. Log detailed errors server-side only.
- Rate limit all AI-powered API routes.
- Body measurements and user photos are sensitive — verify strict RLS policies before any related feature is built.

---

## What NOT To Do
- Do not use the Pages Router.
- Do not use the `any` TypeScript type.
- Do not call Supabase or Gemini from client components.
- Do not create new UI primitives when one already exists in `components/ui/`.
- Do not add new npm packages without first checking if the functionality already exists in the project.
- Do not remove, delete, or modify any code outside the exact scope of the current task.
- Do not add placeholder or mock data in production code paths.
- Do not use raw `<img>` tags — always use Next.js `<Image>`.
- Do not store sensitive data without confirming RLS policies are in place.
- Do not show raw OpenAI responses or stack traces to the user.
- Do not use localStorage for anything sensitive.
- Do not leave TODO comments in completed features.
